column1: Before 2018, which country will be the first to experience two or more anti-government mass protests within one week?
column6: ['Non-US Politics']
column11: An anti-government mass protest is one which involves more than 1,000 participants, and at which participants call for the removal of a national political leader or leaders, change in how national political leaders are selected, or secession. For the question to resolve as yes, the second protest must begin while the first protest is ongoing or within a week of the first protest ending. If none of the countries listed in the answer options experience two or more anti-government mass protests within a week before 2018, the question will resolve with the answer "None of the above". Recent examples of mass protests include the ones that occurred in Bahrain, Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Tunisia, and Yemen in 2010-2011. Jacobin. That's a good one. I wouldn't look so much to the Jacobin for signs to a potential uprising just as I wouldn't look to Adbusters (https://adbusters.org/) as an indicator. Those countercultural icons are as much establishment as the establishment they eschew. It just points to a counterculture image or undercurrent yet gives no real signal whether social disruption will erupt. I would look for other signs. For example, if we look at the Arab Spring riots in 2011, a number of different factors acting in confluence led to popular unease which just required a match to spark the fire.

Took number of years from 2011 to 2016 - 24 years counting 2011. Determined approximately how many years each country experienced mass protests each of those years - a total of 14 years. Determined that there is a mass protest in these countries slightly less than every two years the past 6 years. There are 15 months left in the challenge period. I estimated the chances of a mass protest in the 4 countries for that period overall at 70%. Then i did a similar calculation for each separate country raising the percentage for Jordan due to the instability from the Syrian war. Lowered the percentage for Morocco because its last mass anti-government protests appear to be four years old. Raised it for Egypt and Tunisia due to their extreme instability over past 6 years and anti-government protests in 2016.
